        "answer_count": 1,
        "title": "Calculate procedures or queries in hibernate in my entitys",
        "body": "<p>I have a table called &quot;Endoso&quot;, this table has the properties of &quot;id&quot;, &quot;numEndoso&quot;,&quot;endosos_por_dia&quot;. The &quot;numEndoso&quot; is the id of the envio(id of table EnvioRemesa), and the &quot;endosos_por_dia&quot; property is a calculated property as I put below.<\/p>\n<pre><code>select count(*)\nfrom documento d\ninner join remesa r\non r.id = d.remesa_id\ninner join envio_remesa er\non r.id = er.remesa_id\nwhere r.id=?\n<\/code><\/pre>\n<p>What I want and can't do, is that for example when I calculate endosos_por_dia if 8 documents turn out, create 8 different records in my database, increasing from 1 to 8.And how could I put my calculated property query on my entity Endoso and it will be reflected in the database? How can I do this in hibernate?<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 67502279,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "spring",
            "hibernate"
        ],
        "score": 1,
        "is_answered": false,
        "view_count": 90
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [{
        "owner": {
            "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0f5475dabd0855386f112f93d497e18e?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
            "account_id": 120777,
            "user_type": "registered",
            "user_id": 313400,
            "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/313400/guillaume",
            "reputation": 14744,
            "display_name": "Guillaume"
        },
        "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
        "score": 0,
        "is_accepted": false,
        "last_activity_date": 1620821170,
        "creation_date": 1620821170,
        "body": "<p>You can use a Formula:<\/p>\n<pre><code>@Formula(&quot;(select count(*) ... where r.id=numEndoso)&quot;)\npublic int getEndososPorDia() {\n  return endososPorDia;\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n<p>Note that <code>numEndoso<\/code> in the SQL fragment refers to the ID of your entity, you might need to adapt it because I assumed that it was the name of the column.<\/p>\n<p>This will make the <code>endososPorDia<\/code> field read-only as far as Hibernate is concerned, you will need to modify the underlying data (add new documents) and then refresh the entity to update the value<\/p>\n",
        "answer_id": 67503300,
        "question_id": 67502279
    }],
